tip.text: This little neighbourhood market boasts 40 stalls selling gourmet foods, vintage bric-a-brac, crafts, cakes and preserves, clothing, jewellery - and more than its fair share of hipsters. Still, though, not a bad way to spend a Sunday.

The Village Green Market in Hackney is a perfect place to spend a slow-paced hungover Sunday. Here you'll be greeted with food from Cast Iron Kitchen and Mama Jerk Station, a smattering of craft and vintage clothes stalls and a bicycle repairs pit-stop.

If there was any doubt about the level of cash being splashed in London Fields, Mare Street Market is the definitive proof. In a huge, ornately decorated space, this is a curated 'best of' selection of Hackney businesses: coffee from Flying Horse Coffee; (expensive) flowers from Rebel Rebel; vinyl from Stranger Than Paradise records; a rotating pop up shop selling something artisan and expensive; an antique furniture shop; a deli; and both an open kitchen and restaurant.

With all that under one roof, this is most certainly set to become a blue-tick-verified Hackney hangout. Not a place to come if you're a little strapped, but if you want to sample some top quality produce, see a venue with a super high attention to detail, or just kick it somewhere pleasant, it's definitely worth your time.

Pretty much a mini Broadway Market, Netil is hot on food, crafts and especially bric-a-brac. On top of 15 permanent shops - including a florist, a barbershop, a jewellers and plenty of street food vendors - there's around 15 additional market stalls every Saturday. It’s the brainchild of a local creative community based nearby at Netil House which has focused on giving space to local designers.

Chilled Saturday afternoon vibes, good tunes playing - try and get a spot on the raised sun deck once the weather hots up.

Broadway Market is the street market to end all street markets; rowdy pubs, delicious food from independent stalls, pretty cafes and funked-up gift shops all line the streets. Best explored on the weekend with a hangover.



Opening Times - Saturday: 09:00 to 17:00

Get set for a leafy park market with more organic, seasonal, fresh and local produce than you can shake a stick at. Victoria Park market pops up on the beautiful pedestrianised street between Bonner Gate and Gore Gate called the Nightwalk every Sunday. Expect fruit and veg, farm butchers, fresh fish, baked bread, cakes and biscuits, cheeses, pies, olives, pasta, biltong, raw honey, olive oils, ice creams, coffee, natural wines and craft beers. All at artisan-inflated prices.

Expect a crowd full of cool cats and vintage hunters at this boot sale in Stoke Newington. Plenty of retro garms and valuables that might brighten up that wardrobe of yours. £3 entry and if you're expecting to walk away with something you actually wanna wear, get there early.

Once upon a time, there existed a market on a patch of Kingsland Road named the ‘waste’ market - a rather ramshackle place where people would trade their unwanted bits: old toys, rusty doorknobs, second-hand underwear, that type of thing. Well, it's making a comeback! Kind of. It's been rebranded as the Kingsland Market and has cleaned up its act a little, hitting prospective buyers with vintage furniture, antiques, and that mesmerising mashup of trash and treasure that London markets do so well. It’s on every Saturday.

An oasis of foliage and flowers with everything from bedding plants to 10 foot banana trees up for grabs. This is the perfect place to come freshen up your home on a Sunday, all in prep for the week ahead. Alongside the Sunday market you'll find a host of independent galleries and shops selling pottery, perfume and the like.

Welcome to Europe's longest market, the beating heart of East London borough Waltham Forest. Cockneys have been shouting at the tops of their lungs about fish, veg and meat on this high street since 1885, so as you can imagine the vibe is very much authentic and local. The ever-changing face of the community means that you can expect all sorts of Caribbean and Asian foodstuffs as well as the British classics.

Stalls we hear are worth investigating: SeaFayre (fresh fish from Kent); Giggly Pig (free-range pigs from down the road in Romford) and Quarry Farm (ethical veal).

A little rough around the edges it might be, but the moment you step into Seven Sisters Indoor Market you're transported to a vibrant community market in Bogota, where South American locals meet to eat, drink, chat and chill at all times of day. In this shabby maze, various Spanish accents fill the air - it's an integral hub, and one of the best things about Seven Sisters.

In the various nooks there are over 100 Latin American traders offering services of all kinds: from hairdressers to South American supermarkets; internet cafes to beauty shops; and of course a couple of restaurants and cafes. Grab some of that sweet and delicious Colombian coffee or chomp down on a filling £1 empanada (or something else beige and tasty). Now here's hoping the developers don't get their way and turn this place into a 'pasta express'.

Vegans eh... give 'em an inch and they take a mile - this mile being a weekly slot of street food, music and vibes at The Old Truman Brewery on Brick Lane. Seems like monthly Vegan Nights wasn't enough, with queues around the block, so now you can get your plant-based fix every Sat and Sun under cover of fairy lights.

There's milkshakes, pizzas, wraps, curries, tofish 'n' chips, and huge seitan burgers dripping in saucy sauce. Most of the food leans towards the slutty, junk foody end of the scale, but there's still a few healthier bites to be had like the Ethiopian veggie dips and bread, and all sorts of yummy quiches.

Oh and there's DJs too.

This underground market is a real treasure trove of garms, trinkets and other vintage wares for your wardrobe or your gaff. Step through the nondescript door on Brick Lane and down the stairs to the basement and you'll find a maze of different stalls for you to peruse. Each time you think you've seen it all, you'll notice a door that leads to entirely different section and dozens more pedlars and their wares. Be ready for crowds, however, as it gets pretty packed on market days.

Built way back in 1876, Old Spitalfields Market is one of the finest surviving Victorian market halls on the streets of London.

Alongside selling collectable antiques and great food, this market is a hotspot for finding clothes from up-and-coming designers as well as bohemian, vintage and African designs. There's also many a good bite to be had from some street food top dogs. Bao buns, fresh pasta, the best dumplings in London - go now and go hungry. Sheltered roofing is also in place to keep you shopping happily whatever the weather.

A stone's throw away from Spitalfields Market is the more underrated Petticoat Lane, where you'll find just a little bit of everything: vintage clothing, housewares, textiles, toys, and more, all happily cluttered about. The prices are generally quite cheap, and feature a lot of designer knock-offs (but you can still find some unique pieces here too). This 17th Century market is definitely worth a walk around once you've exhausted all the larger London markets, or if they've just gotten a little too trendy.

The meat-free parade is going from strength to strength these days, so it was about time Kerb got involved. Open three days a week this meat-free market offers all sorts of tasties to the suited and booted of Liverpool Street. If you're in the area at lunchtime, you could certainly do worse than this lot.

Get your hungry self down there for some Indian curries, seitan salt beef bagels from Vegals, coconutty Thai curries from Greedy Khao, jackfruit vegan burgers, and Vietnamese bahn mi bai. Strangely the market does feature fish, but who are we to quibble when there's a black cod bao from BAO - actual heaven in a bun.

This street food market is v popular with the worker bees of East London, and for good reason too. Sandwiched between hectic Old Street and the minimal world of the Barbican, it's a pretty charming and buzzy little spot.

Check out Luardo's, purveyor of Latin American street food, Vietnamese grub from Chao and The Frenchie's duck confit brioche burgers. There's some nifty veggie options too, including a heavenly buddha bowl from er Buddha Bowl. We gobbled up that massaman curry, carrot and homemade kimchi pickle, kale, brown rice, seeds and halloumi and felt v enlightened.

address.line1: Waltham Forest Community Hub 18A Orford Rd

tip.text:
With exceptional produce and hot food on offer, this weekly market is bringing together the best that Walthamstow has to offer. It's a truly local affair, featuring residents and local micro businesses hawking their wares. It a pretty small affair, and what's in store really depends one when you go, but we've been known to tuck into a savoury crepe or two.

The best bit? It's set in the adorable Walthamstow Village, which is just the flipping cutest.

Exmouth Market balances scenic and lively perfectly. It kinda makes you believe in 'village London' with its independent shops spilling out onto the street, buzzy coffee shops and cute fairy lights. As if the restaurants along it aren't choice enough, the weekday market stalls have us salivating all over the shop.

When Spinach & Agushi are there, we get their delicious Ghanaian curry with plantain and a cheeky dab of their ruthless chilli sauce. Other winners are Trastevere' chicken saltimbocca and big players Moro dolling out the most aromatic of meats. Savour-able veggie options can be found if you're precocious enough but BBQ meats reign the roost.

This isn't the kind of market you'd cross town for, it's a pretty small affair, but if you are lolloping about the Finsbury Park/Crouch Hill area and fancy an organic mooch then this could be just the ticket. It may not be a large one, but stalls here rotate so you can always find a slightly different selection of British produce for your fridge and some street-foody bits too.

There's raw Jersey and Guernsey milk and unpasteurised butter and cream; there's artisanal sourdough wheat, spelt and rye bread; there's fruits and veggies (mainly from Kent); and some free-range poultry, pastries, jams, pickles and such. And most importantly, the object of all our desires, those Scandinavian cinnamon and cardamom buns.

This bustling weekend market is the beating heart of Bermondsey, the place to come if you like the taste, smell or look of delicious food. It's kinda mad how many different amazing food stalls they manage to cram into this teeny passage - from jerk to gyoza to waffles, they've got it all - not to mention the permanent shops along the opposite side which feature a branch of St. John and one of our favourite tapas spots in the city, Bar Tozino.

The whole thing is shadowed by dozens of huge flags, bunting and the Shard, which makes for a real 'Pride of London' vibe. Unsurprisingly the place is heaving whenever it's open, so you'll have to just tolerate the crowds - especially when everyone is doing at least two laps to scope out all the offerings.

A quieter, more focused answer to the madness of Maltby Street Market, this collection of Saturday wholesalers makes for a lovely spot to peruse some high-end goods for your pantry (lol, obviously you don't have a pantry, but they don't know that). Cured and raw meats, cheese, honey, and beers can all be found tucked under separate railway arches here - we'd suggest a leisurely stroll past them all so you can bag some free samples to make a more informed decision as to who will get your cash.

It's wet and smelly but Billingsgate is one of those once in a life time markets you've just got to visit.

Trading wholesale fish and seafood through the early hours, a trip here takes plenty of planning and most importantly an early night. Produce is extremely fresh and varied making it a good place to pick up fish for cooking at home.

For those of you who ain't got a clue when it comes to seafood, there’s a training school to help you keep your head above the water.

Perfect for us die-hard market fans: when the weather gets a little too nippy to be wandering about outside, head to Wood Street Market you'll find a collective of 25 local designers, vintage retailers, artists, and food vendors. A great place to come to buy artwork directly from the artists, get some gifts, pick up some antiques and while away a few hours.

This London classic has a strong cult following but it's still worth a roam despite the hoards of tourists. In fact if you get your timings right (early af) it's a darn right charmer.

Check out Northfield Farm for rare-breed meat, Furness for fish and game, Elsey & Bent for fruit and veg, and Flour Power City Bakery for organic loaves. Lunch time offerings are plenty good too - think hog roasts, British pies, Ethiopian stews and a life changing cheese toastie from Kappacasein. It comes filled with Montgomery cheddar, Ogleshield, Comte cheese, five types of onion and packs a cheesy punch.

listing.name: Flea Market at Flat Iron Square
listing.subtitle: Vintage Market

tip.text: Here's the thing about flea markets: they're usually a bloody darn pain. Who has time to rummage around dust-covered rubbish in hopes that you'll find that one gem amongst moth-eaten gingham dresses? Flea at Flat Iron Square is cutting out the crap, bringing you curated vintage and other goodies from around the globe. Flea has you covered for all your clothing, furniture, ceramics, spectacles, books, magazines, and vinyl needs. There's also a bar and scrummy street food stalls if you're in need of shopping fuel.

For those times when you're hungry but you don't know what for, Flat Iron Square has all the answers. This is a foodie hub near to London Bridge comprising of seven railway arches stuffed with restaurants, cafes, bars and street food vendors. Highlights include Portuguese restaurant Bar Douro and Ekachai serving classic Malay, Thai and Cantonese dishes.

Visit the website for specific traders' opening times.

Who the bloody hell needs Pret when you've got Leather Lane Market? Not only is it conveniently located slap bang in the middle of Farringdon for all the workslices out there, but also offers up some seriously tasty grub for around only a fiver a pop.

Jacket spuds, Korean noodles and a good ol' faithful falafel wraps are all up for grabs here - as well as fresh fruit 'n' veg and some flowers.

We’re all for an endearingly ramshackle market that transports you around the world in 30 stalls, and the Nags Head Market is one such place. It's been around since the 70s, serving the local community with all their needs: be that buying fish or meat, having a trim, repairing their shoes, buying gemstones (?), or having their tarot cards read. And, of course, it does loads of inexpensive street food with Japanese, Korean, Colombian, Indian, Turkish, Chinese and Lebanese cuisines all represented by very affable owners.

It's pretty small and rough around the edges - there's undoubtedly some good stuff to be had here but undoubtedly some strange and useless stuff too. For a cheap eat and a transportive experience, enter this community hub and try your luck.

Milan’s street food market has opened a huge 45,000 sqft venue in South London. It's all very wholesome, with a focus on produce from local businesses and small scale farmers. More than just a place to eat, there'll also be a barbershop, a garden, a boxing gym, a cinema, workshops and live performances.

Strut along to the inner courtyard of grand Rosewood London hotel for sustainable, local,organic and wholesome (s.l.o.w. geddit?) produce at their weekly Sunday Market.

Definitely more luxe than your standard local farmers market with goods ranging from artisan charcuterie to apothecary.


Time: 10:30am - 3:00pm

Waterloo can be a bit of dead zone in terms of local community spirit, that is until you turn the corner into Lower Marsh. You'll soon be swallowed up by stalls selling everything from exotic street food to crafts and records. It's a bit of a newbie having been around since 2013, but we think it's kinda cute.

Weekdays you'll catch us hitting up the tasty stalls of Moroccan, Senegalese, Chinese or falafels (keep an eye out for Lagniappe's Trinidad-inspired curries). On Saturdays stall numbers multiply to include gifts, crafts and random so-and-sos clearing out the contents of their loft. And most important date for your diary; the third Saturday of every month, you might catch the vintage car show in all its colourful and eccentric glory. Whichever way you butter your bread, make sure to grab one of Raffo & Ridgeway's inventive cupcakes.

Deptford Market Yard started life as a disused train carriage housing a cafe and community event space. It has now flourished into a small complex inside Deptford's converted railway arches complete with 14 arches, 7 shops and 2 restaurants. Come for clothes shops and gift shops, a unisex hairdressers, circus fit, jerk chicken, bacon naanwiches and a florist.

Check stores and restaurants for individual opening times.

Saturday's in Deptford are won over by a trip to this zesty street food and craft market. In the hubbub of Market Yard - amongst breweries, restaurants and railway arches - lies this relative newbie to the London market scene.

Here like-minded traders lay out fresh farm produce, cheesy wares, vegan bites and artisan crafts by the table load. There's drinks to be drunk, spicy dosas to be nibbled and even music to wiggle to. So grab your most eco tote bag and go fill it up.

Every Saturday, a short stretch of Holloway Road comes to life with this awesome market where you can get your foodie needs met by independent, local traders. They’ve got all the basics, from fresh fruit and veg and free-range meat to cheese and charcuterie – um yes, charcuterie is totally a basic.

Alongside these, you can find stalls hawking global grub like Trinidadian jerk chicken, Greek spanakopita, and Georgian stuffed cheesy bread (!), plus coffee and pastries. While you’re at it, browse through the books at ‘Word on the Street’ and check out African textiles and custom carpentry. The perfect Saturday afternoon.

This was once the home to a world famous fruit and veg market, but in what was probably a classic chicken/egg situation, the hordes of tourists have driven away the plants and made room for a more profitable entity: souvenirs.

The stuff here is a step above the usual tourist fodder however, with a generally high-bar for quality goods from art prints, craft goods and trinkets to furniture, antiques and jewellery. Monday is antique/collectable day and the rest of the week is 'Arts and Crafts' with rotating sellers, so it's worth having a poke around every so often to see what's new. Just be prepared for swarms of people with selfie sticks, backpacks and little fold-up tube maps.

A car park in Peckham where you can hang out, eat street food, drink cocktails, and go wild on the 'gram... stop us if you've heard this one before. Peckham Levels is a grand old project with lofty ambitions, taking over a pissy, desolate car park and converting it into a creative community hub. Its seven floors will be transformed into part studio space, part public hangout - a place for the local creative community to work, collaborate, and do overpriced yoga by candlelight.

The first five floors will be studio space for local artists, designers, architects, and other makers and doers, but it's the top two floors that will really be of practical interest to you. Here you've got seven street food traders (including Caribbean staple Drum & Flats, local Kurdish cafe Nandine, Chinese street food Hao Hao Chi and chicken burgers from Otherside Fried), a natural wine bar, yoga space, music event venue, and even a hair and beauty salon. One way or another, you're going to find yourself in a selfie. Don't fight it.

An inspirational hub of homemade goodness, where creative minds and delicate fingers collide. You'll always find horde of crafters knocking about selling top notch custom-made goodies here. Retro garms, street food, antiques, vintage knick knacks are also up for grabs. Plus it's set in a World Heritage site.

Held near the Muswell Hill entrance to the park, Ally Pally Farmers' Market is real goodie. On a sunny day, there is no more enjoyable market in London. Thirty stalls of wholesome produce, handmade pies, cakes and biscuits, relishes and sauces, quality meats, and all the usual good stuff. There's plenty to fill your larder with if you're feeling bougie or street food flavours to feast on while you're there: BBQ'd sausages, cheese toasties, crepes and pastrami sandwiches abound.

It's worth the trip for the stelar stall selection alone but then there's the views - trees, people, foliage, skies for miles.

(Not on every Sunday and occasionally held at nearby Campsbourne School - so check before you roll thru. Free parking.)

There are plenty out there who rate Brockley Market as the South East's finest - and likely wouldn't be too pleased with us revealing all in this dramatic exposé. It might be in a college car park but this is a terrific community-minded market that's never too crowded, full of locals and good produce.

The stalls sell all the veg, meat, fish, cheeses, wines & beers, cakes and other miscellaneous food stuffs you could ask for; the street food stalls compliment that with delicious picks such as sourdough pizza, Crosstown Doughnuts and, our pick, Mother Flipper Burgers. Small, but with everything you could ask for - it closes at 2pm though so get there early and do bring cash.

Hot off the heels of the stonkingly successful Vegan Nights at the Truman Brewery comes a permanent fixture in Soho, proving that the vegan flame is still burning brightly. Come bask in its warmth every Saturday from 11am-4pm, where you'll find tasty treats like Jake’s Vegan Steaks, Spicebox's flavoursome curries, Eat Chay's fragrant Vietnamese baguettes and Young Vegan's pie and mash offerings.

Well into it's third century, this fruit and veg market is one of London's oldest. True to its roots, you can grab your 5-a-day, fresh milk and even some leather goods, all alongside more contemporary market items like high-end street food and glittery iPhone cases. At lunchtime it's very popular with office louts, so watch out for a long queue then join it. We struggled to choose between Tongue'n'Cheek's Heartbreaker burger and Greek2Go's souvlaki wrap. Coins were tossed, edibles were bought, and lips were licked in satisfaction.

If you're the good honest meat-fearing type, your hunt for plant-based pleasure stops at Savage Salads. Their halloumi-topped mounds of veg are pretty darn satisfying if you ask us. Oh yeah, you did.

The name Camden Market confusingly encompasses three main sections of marketness: an outdoor clothes market mainly selling knock off hoodies and Native American-style wolf t-shirts; an indoor market where the building itself is far nicer than the hordes of questionable jewellery, novelty soaps and wooden carvings; and lastly the street food hub. It's all worth a gander just in case you find THE perfect festivals trousers, but you'll probably only catch us in the foodie area snaffling up finger food by the (wooden) forkful.

Fried chicken, vegan pies, mac 'n' cheese, noodles, cheese toasties, coconut pancakes, churros and more - you name it they're got it, slathered in some crack-like sauce and served to you for slightly more than you'd like to pay. Still pay it though 'cause you're supporting a small business - and frankly it's damn tasty stuff.

If we told you to spend Saturday sampling the delights of Camden Market you might be gearing up for a salvia-infused tour of orange Chinese food, Bob Marley garms and emotional angst. But not anymore! Camden is getting a whole lot more wholesome with this Saturday farmers market. Taking place within Camden Lock Place, it'll feature all that good stuff, from fruit and veg to fish and bread, cheese, sweet goods and plenty more. Keep your eyes out for Norah's brownies and Vadasz Deli's selection of pickles.

Hidden away in East Dulwich, this off-the-beaten-track and pretty low-key market is small but vibing. Go early on a Friday or Saturday morning to unearth vintage bric-a-brac, jewellery and trinkets alongside street food, organic produce and some home-made baked goods. It's a real community affair over here.

We love food markets so much in London that we'll even brave them when it's tipping it down. Cardinal Place Food Market in Victoria is no exception. Every Thursday they pull out all the stops with award-winning vendors packed into a small area. Duck confit, falafel, paella, Argentinian steak, crepes, Polish hotdogs...it's an international gorge fest.

You know the old saying - one man's shit is another man's sugar. Or something along those lines. Well, that's never so true than at a car boot sale, where if you've got the patience, you might be rewarded with a little bit of treasure. This spot is renowned for chic items and designer garms. Real bargains have been seized here in the past so go on and try your luck.

The urban wasteland that used to sit behind Brixton station has been transformed into an environmentally friendly, up-cycled shipping container space. The large events space is used for pop ups, discobarre (disco meets ballet), cinema screenings, spoken word or music events and community projects. There’s just so much in Pop!

Great value street food and some jazzy shops on the ground floor and banging restaurants on the first floor. Want to delve deeper? There’s a barber on the second floor, and Reprezent Radio are squatting (on a wee holiday from their standard Peckham location).

Our favourite part is that each trader at Pop dedicates 1-4 hours a week to the community in various ways (such as getting young offenders trained up with apprenticeships).

Brixton Market is a hub of culture in South London, it inspired the hit 'Electric Avenue' and even has a Grade II English Heritage listing. Wind your way through two covered sections in the railway arches (Brixton Village) and the two outside areas either side of the railway. The core Afro-Caribbean food part is on Electric Avenue, and if you don't mind wading through the debris you can get some cracking deals and really good quality produce.

North Londoners rejoice! As if Primrose Hill couldn't get any more beautiful, it's going to get spruced up even further with a load of delicious food on display. Running every Saturday morning into the early afternoon, expect an impressive horde of traders at this market who will be readily on hand to feed those hungry tums.

Well if it isn't the Horniman's very own farmers market: a wholesome weekly affair that pops up on Saturday morning and finds good honest folk selling seasonal fruit and veg, artisan bread, organic meat, hot food and other treats from the beautiful surrounds of the Horniman's green gardens. Look out for regulars Cherry Berry juices, The Pie Cart and Zingle Food's tasty falafels and tagines.

This vibrant market is perfect for a chilled Sunday afternoon. Perk up with a coffee from Perks & White or a tasty chicken dumpling - but be quick, as famished south Londoners often grab all the best stuff by mid-day.

Time: 10am - 4pm

4 floors with over 75 sellers... Alfies Antique Market is a vintage wonderland filled with unique furniture, retro homeware and rare, antique clothing. Once you're in, don't plan on coming out anytime soon - it's a jungle in there. But don't let this deter you as rummaging is part of the fun. Plus the rooftop café is like an oasis where weary shoppers can enjoy a full English breakfast while overlooking London's chimney pots. Divine.

Proving you don't need to be big to pack a punch is Venn Street Market - a local community Saturday market doling out plenty of quality produce along with those obligatory community vibes. A speedy browser could get this one done in 10-15 minutes, but where's the fun in that? For there are breads, pastries, fish, meat, veggies, smoothies, chocolate and cheese to peruse.

There are also a few street food options including an increasing vegan presence. That said, the hog roast sandwich is probably the most popular thing on the market. In the summer, those with any sense grab some food from here and take it over to the Common.

A poshed-up food market that comes to life every Saturday morning in Chelsea. Celebrating the world of fine, local, British and International foods, all stalls at this market share a similar passion for top quality produce. Expect a whole lot of fresh baked goods, confectionery, high-end deli goods and fresh fruit and veg.

Get your sorting hat on because there's a whole lot of sifting and sorting to be done at Battersea Car Boot sale. Seasoned vintage lovers keep your eyes peeled for the occasional high end goody, with even names like Acne Studios and Selfridges bopping about. This is probably the most expensive car boot we've been to, and by that we mean an extra squid here and there. The quality is on point though, so prices can't really be sniffed at.

Kerb is a real pimp in the street food scene, rounding up the sexiest and sauciest street food vendors and presenting them in one colourful package, giving hungry lunch goers the chance to peruse and choose the dish most to their liking.

Every other Wednesday, Kerb will be injecting Paddington's (slightly soulless) Sheldon's Square with a bitta va-va-voom, where the square will be stuffed with the sounds of sizzling meats and wafts of oozy, gooey mac & cheese, spicy soto sambal bowls and sugary doughnuts.

An awesome secret in Crystal Palace, this little-weekend-market-that-could boasts two floors jam-packed with all the goodies - antiques, vintage, books, you name it. There is frequently a little farmers' market outside, or head down the road to Crystal Palace Food Market (at the bottom of Haynes Lane), where you'll find even more foodie goodness to feast on.

This 20 year famous weekend market in Kilburn is full of vintage clothes, bric-a-brac, household items and fashion accessories. It's £4 before 11am, 50p after and for good reason, so get there early to snaffle up the quality.

According to their website, you can't sell tins of paint, livestock or counterfeit goods at this one. So if that's the kind of stuff you go to car boots looking to buy, don't bother.

Northcote Road Market has been busting out fruit and veg basics to the locals since like the 1860s. The high street has adapted to its pumpkin peddling ways, and is now packed with butchers and bakeries to complement.

Grab yourself some bits to spice up that chicken you've got in the fridge or stop for a spot of lunch. The food stalls ain't half bad and they wouldn't be out of place on Borough Market. More colourful than the pashminas, “Eat Me Cakes” demand some of your undivided attention. Have a nibble on one of their iced muffins and bag one for later because at a paaand for a large one, it will cost you far more at Starbucks and they'll be lame colours. As well as food, there's local art, vintage clothes and flowers. The antique market at 155a is also well worth a rummage.

An intimate farmers' market on Salusbury Road with a great community feel. They have regularly rotating guest stalls alongside some permanent faces like David and Jane Barkers with their biodynamic Norfolk grown veg or Chad with his premium dairy and coffee. They also have some ready to eat produce, like the ever popular garlic dumplings from The Garlic Farm.

Five minutes from Queen's Park and less from some more than decent pubs, this is a great first stop on any wholesome Sunday.

Iconic, bustling and colourful, Portobello Road Market is a true testament to the history and people of London. Although the area’s gentrification over the past decade or so has seen a shift in the vibe towards the more upmarket, it remains a wonderful and worthy destination.

Crazy market day is Saturday: expect flocks of tourists seeking out the blue door from ‘Notting Hill’ and a motley crew of Portobello’s eclectic characters busking, conversing and wandering about. Arrive hungry and have your pick of the vying vendors, from paella to pancakes, and explore the shops and stalls at your leisure. Whether you’re after classic vinyl, antique jewellery, vintage clothing or that ephemeral “je ne sais quoi,” this famous and historic market is the perfect place to look. Look out for the Moroccan fish stall on Golborne Road - it's killing it.

Pop up stalls with wholesome Streetfoods from all over the world, from burritos, arepes, souvlaki, beef doners, burgers, hot salt beef, surimi prawns, Cuban hog roast, chicken satay even cakes by award winning artisan bakers Breadren.

Opening Times - 10:00 to 17:00 Sat and Sun

Market Hall Fulham has quite cleverly taken an old listed building (what used to be Fulham Broadway station); popped a bar behind the original ticket office booths; and thrown in all sorts of big foodie names. The result? A bustling street food hub complete with bar, deli, food stalls, long tables and - on a busy night - head-shatteringly loud acoustics.

Drinks are tidy (organic wine, cocktails, craft beer) but the food selection is sexy af. You've got absolute classics like Yard Sale pizza and Butchies fried chicken alongside all sorts of unusual bits like liquorice and black sesame soft serve, Indian kahti rolls or top quality smoked brisket. They've even roped in some of the team from Farang to lay on Thai flavours that had us smiling all evening. Who knew peaches would work in a duck curry? Not us - not back then anyway.

North End Road market is an old timer that's been doing its thing since the 1880s. Whether you're after apples 'n' pears, fresh meat, fish, garms, street food, arts and crafts, or just some eye candy for your perusal, there's a little something here for everyone. Especially if everyone is feeling a little low on doe - the produce here is cheap as chips, so you can cop a bowl-full of avo for just a few bob.

With most of the stalls being run by the same families for generations, expect a quintessentially Laandan experience; to be referred to repeatedly as young lady, or son, in spite of your age and to bring home a mixed bag of batteries, misshapen carrots, some plantain and a pair of North End's finest pleather moccasins.

Tooting Market is the neighbourhood's pulsing heart, and one of the main reasons SW17 has drawn so much heat lately. Though it's been around since 1930, a slate of recent openings have helped put the neighbourhood on the map for foodie types. It's also roused cries of gentrification, but isn't that just the way?

Enter through its distinctive red facade - untouched since the market opened - and into an aromatic world of delicious grub from around the globe. Our top tips: start your night slurping ramen at Koi, then wash it down with some delicious G&Ts from Graveney Gin (a tiny tasting room from local distillery of the same name) or some fine fermented grapes from pop-up-turned-perm-stall Unwined. The market gets pretty buzzy on the weekends, when merrymakers flood in for a post-work tipple and some pre-game fodder. Grab some feed from your fave stall and join the crowd - there's plenty places to sit.

Looky looky fruity tooty! This berry good farmer's market is absolutely bursting with all the juicy colours of the rainbow, and even better - it's on every single week. Keep your peepers peeled for March House Farm and their humongous selection of free range rare breed meats on the market; you'll probably end up scoffing one of their beef or lamb 'Hetties - they just look too damn good.

This community farmers market has everything you need, from organic and fresh foods, comfort food to world foods - It's a real food lovers market.

Stuck on what to buy? Try the creamy goats cheeses from Nut Knowle Farm or a homemade apple juice when sun's out.

This Sunday market warms our cockles right up with a tasty selection of locally-sourced produce with international flavour. There's fresh coffee, fish, meat and game, fruit, olives, a Moroccan style stand, juices... tons of tasty treats, basically.

Don't miss the delicious arepas from Mulata - tasty Columbian corn-maize bread stuffed with cheesy goodness. And the best bit: the proceeds go to the Duke Meadows Trust.. aww.

Only showing it's face once a month on the first Sunday of each month, Chiswick Car Boot Sale is one that’s on any car booting rangers calendar. With smashing stalls selling quality bric-a-brac, antiques and unusual homewares, it's no wonder this place is always utterly rammed.

Open for sellers from 7am. Buying starts at 8am- 1pm. Like always arrive early to get the good stuff!

Just a stone's throw from Kew Gardens Station, on every first Sunday of the month, you’ll find a pleasant ol' village market, with good grub and good spirits. Selling all kind of rolls from bread to sausage to cinnamon, the focus here is on artisan food with a side of local crafts which will have you persuaded you could do it yourself at home, except you won't. They’ve also got mad game, fresh fish and a smattering of flower and gift stalls that your mum would be all over.

BYOP (bring your own pooch) for an impromptu win at their regular dog show. All organisers are volunteers and all profits made by the market community go to charity, which is nice. And you're nice. So it's a match made in heaven really.
